With the "Civic DevOps Pipeline" serving as the structural foundation, your Lighthouse repository is ready to move from a conceptual framework to an operational toolset. To truly engage your "Network of Conscience," you need modules that move from theory to actionable application.

Here are three specific functional modules you can add to the Lighthouse repository to make it a practical tool for citizens, bureaucrats, and independent observers:

1. The "Fiscal Impact Transparency" Protocol (The Shark Tank Module)
Since you identified that the "debt trap" is exacerbated by uncosted manifesto promises, this module acts as a "pre-check" for political claims.

Purpose: To force political parties to treat manifestos as financial contracts.

Contents:

The "Feasibility Template": A standardized form for manifestos that requires parties to state: Total Cost, Funding Source, and Projected Fiscal Impact.

The "Sustainability Scorecard": A simple, objective metric (e.g., Debt-to-GSDP ratio, Revenue Expenditure vs. Capital Expenditure) that users can apply to any government policy.

Why it matters: It shifts the conversation from "Do you like this promise?" to "Can we afford this promise?"

2. The "Infrastructure Audit" (Civic QA/QC) Protocol
This module focuses on your goal of "continuous feedback" during public works construction.

Purpose: To turn citizens into the "Quality Assurance" (QA) team for local infrastructure.

Contents:

The "Work-in-Progress (WIP) Audit Checklist": A simple, layman-friendly guide to inspecting public works (e.g., "Is the material used as per the standard?", "Is the project on the timeline?").

The "Bug Report" Template: A standardized, professional template for filing a "Defect Report" with local municipal bodies or IAS officers, using the language of administrative accountability rather than political complaint.

Why it matters: It forces local administrators to explain why a project is failing, moving the focus from "who is to blame" to "what needs fixing."

3. The "RBAC for Democracy" (Societal Permissions Model)
This module codifies the roles of the society's pillars we discussed earlier.

Purpose: To define boundaries for influencers, media, bureaucracy, and citizens.

Contents:

The "Role-Based Access Chart": A clean table clearly mapping what each pillar should and should not do (e.g., Media’s role is Signal Stewardship, not Outrage Amplification).

The "Boundary Guardrails": A clear definition of what constitutes "Noise" (e.g., ad hominem attacks, meme-based mockery, hate speech) versus "Signal" (e.g., policy discussion, fiscal critique).

Why it matters: It provides an objective way to "filter" discourse. When someone starts using "sticker/monkey" tactics, you can point to this module and say: "This falls outside the scope of acceptable Civic Governance discourse."

Strategy for "Socializing" the Lighthouse
Now that the foundation is solid, your transition to "socializing" these ideas should be as systematic as your repository:

The "Lighthouse Landing" (Website/Landing Page): If you haven't already, create a simple GitHub Pages site for your repository. It makes the content look professional and accessible to non-coders (like NGO heads or local administrators).

The "Civic API" Pitch: When speaking to IAS/IPS officers or NGOs, don't ask them to "support your protest." Ask them to "Adopt the Protocol." For example: "Our repository provides a standard protocol for Fiscal Transparency. Could your organization use this to evaluate upcoming project proposals?"

The "Lighthouse Community" (Contribution Guidelines): Use your CONTRIBUTING.md file in the repo to invite others to "pull request" their own audit templates or case studies. This turns a single repository into a collective resource.
